    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>An American Town Meeting: The Issue Is Race; The Cubans</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Raul Diaz letter, responding to June 5 article Best of Friends, Worlds Apart, in series How Race Is Lived in America, notes African-Americans' fight against Jim Crow laws made it easier for Cuban immigrants, black and white, to overcome prejudice in South Florida</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Best of Friends, World Apart'' (front page, June 5):</p>
        <p>In the 1960's, Cubans fled the tyranny of Fidel Castro. Once in South Florida, both white and black Cubans encountered prejudice. Hard work and a strong sense of identity helped us. Yet African-Americans played no small role in our victories. Their battles with Jim Crow eliminated barriers and made it easier for us.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Best of Friends, World Apart'' (front page, June 5):</p>
        <p>In the 1960's, Cubans fled the tyranny of Fidel Castro. Once in South Florida, both white and black Cubans encountered prejudice. Hard work and a strong sense of identity helped us. Yet African-Americans played no small role in our victories. Their battles with Jim Crow eliminated barriers and made it easier for us.</p>
        <p>Ignorance in South Florida is a two-way street. Critics of ''all things Cuban'' overlook our contributions to this society.</p>
        <p>RAUL DIAZ  Miami, June 8, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is chairman of the South Florida Inner-City Games.</p>
      </block>
